WHEN TRAILER CONTAINING THIS SHIPMENT WAS PUT TO THE DOCK AND THE DOORS OPENED, A VERY STRONG ODOR WAS NOTICED.  THE DOORS WERE IMMEDIATELY CLOSED AND THE TRAILER ISOLATED IN THE YARD.  SMITH REIDEL EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY WAS NOTIFIED AND THEY RESPONDED.  THEY ENTERED THE TRAILER WITH LEVEL A SUITS AND FOUND THAT ONLY ONE OF THE CONTAINERS HAD A VALVE THAT WAS NOT COMPLETELY CLOSED.  THE VALVE WAS REPAIRED AND THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

column168: APPROX 10 GALLON OF DIESEL FUEL SPILLED DURING DELIVERY.  PRODUCT IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: DALE STRELOW WAS PUMPING GASOLINE AND WALKED AROUND THE TRUCK TO CHECK CABLE CONNECTION FOR THE REELS.  HE WAS TIGHTENING IT AND HEARD LAUGHING. HE FINISHED AND WALKED AROUND THE TRUCK AND FOUND THE HOSE OUT-OF THE FILL PIPE.  HE SHUT IT OFF IMMEDIATELY & NOTICED SOME KIDS RUNNING OFF THROUGH THE SNOW.  THE OWNER OF COONLAKE MKT. CONTACTED AGASSI ENVIRONMENTAL & THEN SHIRLEY KLINE (OUR OFFICE MANAGER) CONTRACTED W/AGASSI TO CLEANUP SPILL.  WE DO HAVE AN OIL SPILL RESPONSE PLAN AND IT HAS BEEN REVIEWED BY DALE.  HOWEVER, WE FEEL AFTER THIS THAT WE NEED TO HAVE SEMI-ANNUAL MEETINGS TO GO OVER PROCEDURES FOR FILLING & IF A SPILL OCCURS.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: TRUCK COMPLETED A TRANSFER OF CHEMICALS INTO CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK.  AT COMPLETION OF TRANSFER CONSIGNEE'S UNLOADING HOSE CONNECTION BROKE OFF CONSIGNEE'S TRANSFER LINE.  CHEMICAL FLOWED FROM FAILED TRANSFER LINE INTO CONTAINMENT AREA.  CONSIGNEE HANDLED SPILL.

UPON REALIZING THERE WAS A LEAK, THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY STOPPED IN THE PARKING LOT OF A SHELL STATION 6 MILES WEST OF MONETA, VA ON STATE ROUTE 122 IN BEDFORD CCOUNTY AND TOOK ACTION TO CONTAIN THE SPILL BY APPLYING ABSORBENT INSIDE THE TRUCK TRAILER AND ON THE PARKING LOT.  LIQUID WAS LEAKING FROM AROUND THE LID OF ONE CONTAINER.  THE LID WAS REMOVED AND FREE LIQUID WAS PUMPED INTO 55 GALLON DRUMS TO PREVENT FURTHER SPILLAGE DURING TRANSPORT.  THE CONTAINERS WERE NOT SUPPOSED TO CONTAIN FREE LIQUIDS, SO OTHER NON-LEAKING CONTAINERS WERE ALSO CHECKED FOR FREE LIQUIDS.  ONE OTHER CONTAINER HELD FREE LIQUID AND THAT WAS ALSO PUMPED INTO DRUMS.  CONTAMINATED ABSORBENT FROM THE CLEAN-UP WAS PLACED IN DRUMS AS WELL.  ALL DRUMS WERE ADDED TO THE MANIFEST AND WERE TRANSPORTED ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL MANIFESTED LOAD BACK TO ENVIRONMENTAL OPTIONS, WAREHOUSE.  THE GENERATOR WAS CONTACTED, AND HE CAME TO INSPECT THE CONTAINERS.  HIS WASTE DOES NOT NORMALLY CONTAIN FREE LIQUIDS, SO HE SUSPECTS THAT RAINWATER WAS INTRODUCED DURING STORAGE PRIOR TO TRANSPORT. HE PLANS TO CHANGE THE WAY HE STORES HIS WASTE.  THREE DRUMS OF WASTE WERE PRODUCED BY SPILL CLEAN-UP.  TWO DRUMS OF WASTE WERE DELIVERED TO ENCYCLE/TEXAS, 5500 UP RIVER ROAD, CORPUS CHRISTI TX 78407 FOR METALS RECYCLING.  ONE DRUM COULD NOT BE PROCESSED BY ENCYCLE AND WAS RETURNED TO GENERATOR FOR FUTURE DISPOSAL.

column168: DURING UNLOADING IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE OF THE BAGS MUST HAVE BEEN DEFECTIVE.  THE ESCAPED MATERIALS EVAPORATED AND THE LEFT OVER MATERIAL WAS SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: OUR DRIVER HAD BEEN CLEARED FOR DELIVERY AT HIS DESTINATION AND PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD THE FRESH ACID INTO THE STORAGE TANK.  A 3/4" BLEEDER LINE IN THE BLOW DOWN LINE HAD INADVERTENTLY BEEN LEFT OPEN RESULTING IN PRODUCT SPILLING ONTO THE GROUND.  THE CONSIGNEE CLEANED UP THE AREA AND DISPOSED OF THE RESIDUE.

column14: TRACK BETWEEN I40 AND ATSF MAI
column168: THIS RELEASE OCCURRED WHILE THE TANK CAR WAS LOCATED ON A TRACK LEASED BY THE CONSIGNEE.  THE CAR HAD BEEN PARTIALLY UNLOADED SINCE ITS ARRIVAL ON DECEMBER 4, 1995.  A FITTING MANIFOLD HAD BEEN APPLIED TO THE VAPOR VALVE TO PRESSURIZE THE CAR TO PERMIT UNLOADING.  THE UNLOADED MANIFOLD INCLUDED A FLANGED CONNECTION ATTACHED WITH FOUR BOLTS AND A RUBBER GASKET.  A THREADED PIPE FITTING JOINED THE FLANGE AND LEAD TO CUT OFF VALVE (WHICH WAS CLOSED).  THE RELEASE OCCURRED WHEN THE PIPE JOINING THE FLANGE AND VALVE FAILED.  THE CAUSE OF THE FAILURE APPEARED TO BE DETERIORATION OF THE PIPE AND FITTINGS DUE TO REACTION WITH THE PRODUCT.  DUE TO PRESSURE IN THE CAR AND THE LIQUID (UNLOADING) VALVE IN ITS OPEN POSITION, PRODUCT REMAINED IN THE UNLOADING ASSEMBLY.  WHEN THE FAILURE OCCURRED, PRODUCT WAS SPRAYED OUT OF THE CAR.  A TRAIL OF APPROXIMATELY 100 FEET IN LENGTH LEAD RELEASED PRODUCT TO A LOW AREA WHERE POOLING BEGAN.  THE POOL AREA WAS APPROXIMATELY 20 FEET BY 30 FEET.  VAPOR FROM THE POOL AND FROM THE FAILED UNLOADING ATTACHMENT PRODUCED A VAPOR CLOUD THAT FORMED ABOUT TWO HUNDRED FEET ABOVE THE GROUND.  THE CLOUD DRIFTED SOUTHWARD REQUIRING IMMEDIATE CLOSURE OF INTERSTATE 40, WHICH IS IMMEDIATELY SOUTH OF THE RELEASE SITE.  ATSF RESPONDERS WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SITE.  THE RELEASE WAS STOPPED BY CLOSING THE TANK CAR'S LIQUID LINE VALVE.  FOLLOWING SECURMENT OF THE CAR AT 1025 MT, THE INTERSTATE WAS REOPENED TO TRAFFIC AT 1029 MT.  RAIL TRAFFIC HAD ALSO BEEN HELD WHICH RESULTED IN A CUMULATIVE DELAY OF 10:35 AMONG SEVEN TRAINS.  THE SPARSELY POPULATED IMMEDIATE AREA WAS ALSO CLOSED BY RESPONDING AGENCIES.  AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR SELECTED BY THE CONSIGNEE AND STATE RESPONDERS NEUTRALIZED THE POOLED PRODUCT, PERFORMED SOIL SAMPLING AND HANDLED CONTAMINATED SOIL.  THIS RELEASE WAS AN OCCURRENCE AFTER DELIVERY OF THE TANK CAR TO THE CONSIGNEE. IT SHOULD NOT BE CONSIDERED AS A PART OF THE RAILWAY'S PHASE OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TRANSPORTATION CYCLE.

SHIPPER LOADED FREIGHT ON TO ROADRUNNERS TRAILER AT TIME OF PICK UP. DRIVER RETURNED TO THE TERMINAL & OPERATIONS MGR HAD THE DOCK CREW LOAD FREIGHT ON BEHIND THIS FREIGHT. THIS TANK CAR FOUND TO BE RELEASING PRODUCT DURING INBOUND INSPECTION AT YARD.  ATSF RESPONDERS DETERMNED THAT A FAILED WELD WAS PERMITTNG PRODUCT TO SEEP OUT.  IT VAPORIZED QUICKLY UPON RELEASE. THE FAILED WELD WAS IN THE ATTACHMENT OF THE MANFOLD TO THE TANK CAR TANK AND WAS ABOUT FOUR INCHES LONG.

THE NUT WAS TIGHT ON THE ASSEMBLY, AND ALL EFFORTS TO STOP THE RELEASE WERE UNSUCCESSFUL. THE SHIPPER PROVIDED ASSISTANCE VIA PHONE.  AS THIS WAS A CAR EQUIPPED WITH A MAGNETIC GAUGING DEVICE, A FAILED O RING WAS SUSPECTED. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO DIVERT THE CAR TO A LOCAL DISTRIBUTOR FOR UNLOADING.  THE CAR WAS SENT TO A REPAIR SHOP WHEN UNLOADED.

column168: I WAS CALLED TO BAY 168, EAST PRIMARY, TO CLEAN UP A CORROSIVE LIQUID DAMAGE.  AFTER CONSULTING DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR CORROSIVE LIQUIDS, I CHECKED PH. I TOLD HIM AND HIS SUP TO GO RUN WATER ON IT FOR 15 MINUTES, FILL OUT AN ACCIDENT REPORT, AND GO TO DR.  HE DID.  AFTER PH READ 7, BROUGHT BACK TO DOT CAGE WHERE I PROCESSED THROUGH DMP PROCEDURES.

ENGINE FOREMAN REPORTED THAT VAPOR WAS RELEASED FROM THE CAR AS HE COUPLED INTO THE TANK CAR.  ALTHOUGH HE DECLINED MEDICAL ATTENTION, HE DID ADVISE OF A ONE TIME INHALATION OF ACID VAPOR.  ATSF RESPONDERS FOUND THAT ALL FOUR OF THE UNLOADING VALVE FLANGE BOLTS WERE TWO TO THREE FULL TURNS LOOSE.  THESE WERE TIGHTENED AND NO FURTHER RELEASE WAS DETECTED.  NO LIQUID PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: SHORTLY BEFORE 0400 OUR DRIVER (WHO WAS ENROUTE FROM ANAHEIM, CA. TERMINAL TO SAN JOSE TERMINAL) MADE A WESTBOUND TURN ONTO FERGUSON RD (FROM PACHECO PASS/HWY 152).  WITHIN A HALF MILE FROM THE TURN (ONTO WESTBOUND FERGUSON RD) HE SWERVED TO MISS A COW IN THE MIDDLE OF THE ROADWAY AND OVERTURNED HIS TRACTOR AND 28' DOUBLES TRAILER.  DURING HIS SKID HE STRUCK THE CORNER OF A OCCUPIED HOUSE CAUSING DAMAGE TO IT BEFORE THE EQUIPMENT CAME TO REST.  THE DRIVER SUSTAINED CUTS TO HIS FACE AND BROKE HIS ARM.  NO ONE WAS INJURED IN THE HOUSE AND NO OTHER VEHICLES WERE INVOLVED.  THE CALIFORNIA HWY PATROL RESPONDED AND OUR DRIVER WAS AIRLIFTED TO A NEARBY HOSPTIAL.  THE AREA FIRE DEPT. MADE ARRANGEMENTS WITH A COMPANY TO CLEAN THE PAINT SPILL OF THE 16000 LBS.  PAINT SHIPMENT, 4100 LBS WAS FLAMMABLE. ALTHOUGH APPROXIMATELY 175 GALLONS BEACHED, ACTUAL SPILLAGE WAS MINIMAL (EVEN THOUGH THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT WAS HAULED AWAY BY THE CLEANUP COMPANY). OUR DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO REMAIN ON HWY 152 UNTIL HWY 101 (WHERE THEY GET ON THE HWY TO HEAD NORTH TOWARD SAN JOSE, CA.).  THEY HAVE BEEN CAUTIONED ABOUT THE IMPORTANCE OF PAYING CLOSE ATTENTION TO THE ROADWAY (DURING THE APPROX. LAST 3 MILES PRIOR TO ENTERING N/B HWY 101).

AT APPROXMATELY 0735 HOURS ON JANUARY 04, 1996, LONZA INC. RELEASED A CLOUD OF  CHLORINE GAS DURING THE TRANSFER PROCESS FROM TANK CAR GATX 25785 INTO A STORAGE TANK.  CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT IS UNKNOWN; HOWEVER, BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES INSPECTOR L.E. KERTING - AT CONRAIL'S REQUEST - INSPECTED AND FOUND THE FOLLOWING ON THE TANK CAR, THE STOPPED FOR THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER WAS PARTIALLY CUT OFF WITH CUTTING TORCH WHICH ALLOWED THE COVER WHEN OPENED THE REST ON THE TANK CAR UNLOADING CONNECTIONS.  SEC. 179. 100-12(C).  THE PORT HOLE COVERS ON THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING ON THE 'A' END AND THE LEFT SIDE WERE FLAPS OPENING THE VERTICAL POSITION AND THE 'B' END AND THE RIGHT SIDE WERE TEAR DROPS OPENING THE HORIZONTAL POSITION;"  AS A PRECAUTION, NINE CONRAIL EMPLOYEES WERE EXAMINED AT HOSPITAL AND RELEASED TO RETURN TO WORK.

FEDEX SHUTTLE ROUTE 55 ENROUTE FROM LAX-JDY (SANTA FE SPRINGS) WHEN THE ENGINE CAUGHT ON FIRE (CAUSE IS STILL UNDETERMINED).  THE DRIVER ESCAPED UNINJURED.  THE VEHICLE WAS 80% FULL AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT.  THE RADIOACTIVE PACKAGING WAS NOT COMPROMISED.  THE RECIPIENT CAME TO THE SCENE, PERFORMED A WIPE TEST, TOOK READINGS AND DETERMINED THAT NO CONTAMINATION WAS PRESENT. WE ALSO FOUND A LABEL ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRUCK THAT INDICATED ETIOLOGIC AGENT.  WE FOUND AN HIV TEST KIT FROM ABBOTT LABS.  PER DR. RICK KNUTSON - CDC IN ATLANTA- THE KIT PROBABLY DID NOT CONTAIN A VIABLE MICRO ORGANISM.  BUT, IF IT DID, THE HEAT FROM THE FIRE KILLED IT.  WE ALSO FOUND A BOTTLE OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID FROM A CONSUMER COMMODITY SHIPMENT.

FROM THE INFORMATION LISTED ON THE MSDS IT WAS ASCERTAINED THAT THERE WERE FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS OF VARIOUS TYPES IN THE FIBERBOARD BOX. THERE WERE "NO" HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MARKINGS, LABELS, ON THE OUTER BOX NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN EVIDENCE WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION OF THE FAA FOR INVESTIGATION.

column168: DRIVER SLID ON SLICK ROADS.  ROLLED TRUCK AND TRAILER INTO MEDIUM.  I.S.P. RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY.  R.M.I. HAS TAKEN CARE OF ALL CLEAN UP.  THE DRIVER WAS FIRED DUE TO INATENTIVE DRIVING AS WELL AS OTHER WRITE-UPS.

THE INNER PACKAGE IS A DRY DEWAR.  THIS DEWAR WHEN PROPERLY PACKAGED WILL HAVE LIQUID NITROGEN POURED INTO IT, TIME WILL ALLOW THE INNER CORE TO ABSORB THE LIQUID NITROGEN, AND BEFORE THE SPECIMEN IS PLACED IN THE DEWAR, THE EXCESS LIQUID NITROGEN IS POURED OUT.  THE DEWAR IS VENTED TO ALLOW GAS THAT HAS BUILT UP TO ESCAPE.  THIS DEWAR WAS TIPPED OVER INADVERTENTLY.  WHEN THE TIP OCCURED, LIQUID NITROGEN WAS SEEN TO BE POURING OUT OF THE DEWAR.  D.O.T. LAW STIPULATES THAT A DRY DEWAR IS NOT REGULATED AS LONG AS THER IS NO STANDING LIQUID NITROGEN IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DEWAR.  IN THIS CASE, FOR LIQUID NITROGEN TO FLOW FREELY OUT OF THE DEWAR, THERE WOULD HAVE TO BE STANDING LIQUID IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DEWAR. I CALLED THE SHIPPER THIS MORNING AND SPOKE TO DOROTHY DIMAGBIA.  SHE SAID THAT THEY FILLED THE DEWAR YESTERDAY MORNING.  SHE DID NOT INDICATE THAT ANY WAS POURED OFF UNTIL I PROMPTED HER.  EVEN IF THAT WAS ACCOMPLISHED AS SHE INDICATED, THERE WAS A SIGNIFICANT AMOUNT OF LIQUID REMAINING IN THE DEWAR WHEN IT WAS TENDERED TO FEDEX.  I CALLED THE LAX CASFO THIS MORNING AND SPOKE TO JIM WISEMAN AT 11:08 CST.  I ADVISED HIM ON THE SITUATION AND GAVE ALL OF THE ABOVE INFORMATION.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS, OR OTHER INDICATOR(S) THAT WOULD HAVE LED US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.  FEDEX IN SAN DIEGO WILL HOLD THE FREIGHT PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: TRACTOR AND TANK TRAILER WERE PROCEEDING SOUTHBOUND ON I-45 ABOUT 10 MILES NORTH OF CONROE, TEXAS, AT 6:37PM, ON JANUARY 23, 1996.  IT WAS NIGHT IN A DRIVING RAINSTORM.  THE AUTOMOBILE IN FRONT OF THE TRACTOR/TANKER TRAILER BRAKED SUDDENLY.  THE TRACTOR/TANKER TRAILER BRAKED AND JACK-KNIFED.  THE FORCE OF THE JACK-KNIFING RIPPED THE FIFTH WHEEL OFF OF THE TRACTOR AND CAUSED THE TRAILER TO ROLLOVER INTO THE DITCH ON THE SIDE OF THE ROAD.  NO VEHICLES OTHER THAN THE TRACTOR/TANK TRAILER WERE INVOLVED IN THE ACCIDENT.  THE FORCE OF THE IMPACT CAUSED THE DOME LID OF THE TRAILER TO OPEN.  815 GALLONS OF COMBUSTIBLE LIQUID, N.O.S. ETHYLENE GLYCOL MONOBUTYL ETHER SPILLED INTO THE DITCH.  THE CONROE, TEXAS FIRE AND POLICE EMERGENCY REPONSE CO-OP RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL CORP. AND SLAY TRANSPORTATION CO., INC. EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAMS WERE ATIVATED.  I-45 WAS SHUT DOWN AND TRAFFIC RE-ROUTED.  DRIVER WAS TREATED FOR MINOR INJURIES AND RELEASED AT A LOCAL HOSPITAL.  DRIVER WAS ALSO DRUG AND ALCOHOL TESTED.  TRACTOR AND TANK TRAILER WERE DISABLED AT THE SCENE AND TOWED. SITE OF SPILL WAS DIKED AND REMEDIATED.  DIRT 1 INCH BY 50 FEET BY 6 FEET WAS REMOVED AND DISPOSED.  AREA WAS SODDED.

column168: FOLLOWING IS THE PRELIMINARY INCIDENT REPORT OF THE 18 WHEEL VEHICLE CARRYING CALCIUM CARBIDE UN1402 FOR THE CARBIDE/GRAPHITE GROUP, INC. THAT OCCURRED ON JANUARY 1, 1996 AT APPROXIMATELY 6:30 P.M. AT THE I-264 EXIT RAMP AT BROWNSBORO ROAD. AFTER INVESTIGATION AND A DISCUSSION WITH THE DRIVER OF THE UNIT INVOLVED, IT APPEARS THE DRIVER WAS EN ROUTE TO A CUSTOMER LOCATED IN RICHMOND, VIRGINIA. THE DRIVER WAS EAST BOUND ON I-264 WHEN HE FAILED TO EXIT ONTO I-64 EAST, AND THEN PROCEEDED TO THE BROWNSBORO ROAD EXIT WHERE HE COULD MANEUVER A TURNAROUND. IT IS THOUGHT THAT THE DRIVER, WHILE ON THE EXIT RAMP, TO AVOID A COLLISION WITH THREE VEHICLES SITTING AT THE SPOTLIGHT AT THIS LOCATION, MANEAUVERED HIS VEHICLE TO THE LEFT SHOULDER OF THE ROAD AND CONTINUED TO THE INTERSECTION. THE DRIVER IN THE FIRST VEHICLE STARTED THROUGH THE INTERSECTION WHEN THE UNIT STRUCK THE SIDE OF THE FIRST VEHICLE. THE DRIVER TURNED THE UNIT SHARPLY TO THE RIGHT WHICH CAUSED THE UNIT TO TURN OVER ON IT'S LEFT SIDE. AS A RESULT, FIVE OF THE EIGHT DOT SPEC. 56 CONTAINERS LOADED WITH APPROXIMATELY 1200 LBS OF MATERIAL ON THE ROADWAY. THIS MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP BY THE HARRODS CREEK FIRE DEPARTMENT WITH SUPERVISON BY REPRESENTATIVES OF THE CARBIDE/GRAPHITE GROUP AND PUT INTO 55 GALLON DRUMS AND RETURNED TO OUR FACILITY FOR REUSE. AFTER THE MATERIAL WAS REMOVED FROM THE SITE, THE SITE WAS THEN SWEPT CLEAN AND HARRODS CREEK FIRE DEPT. WASHED THE ROAD. THE RESULTING SLURRY BECOMES CALCIUM HYDROXIDE WHICH IS NOT A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. THE DRIVER WHO PREVIOUSLY HAD AN OUTSTANDING DRIVING RECORD, WAS INSTRUCTED TO USE A LESS CONGESTED AREA WHEN ATTEMPTING A TURNAROUND, OR A CHOOSE AN ALTERNATE ROUTE WHEN PRACTICAL
CUSTOMER'S PETROMETER MALFUNCTIONED.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON ROUTE 80 AND PULLED INTO A REST AREA NEAR THE TOWN OF MILESBURG AT 0530 WITH A LOADED TANK TRAILER OF NITRIC ACID. WE WERE REQUIRED TO TRANSFER THE LOAD INTO ANOTHER TRAILER, WHICH WE DID. LESS THAN 8 OUNCES OF ACID WERE RELEASED ONTO THE PAVEMENT. THE HAZMAT TEAM PLACED A PVC CATCH BASIN BELOW THE DRIPPING DISCHARGE LINE. THE INTERNAL VALVE SEAT ON THE LEAKING TRAILER WAS DAMAGED AND HAD TO BE REPLACED.

column168: DURING A ROUTINE TIRE AND LOAD INSPECTION A LEAKER WAS DISCOVERED.  AT 9:00PM, LEAD TECH ALFRED SANTILLANES, RECEIVED A CALL FROM RICHEM EMERGENCY  RESPONSE COORDINATOR GARY MICHAELSON, INFORMING HIM OF A TRL TRACTOR TRAILER IN THE AMARILLO, TX AREA, LEAKING POSSIBLE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FROM THE REAR OF THE UNIT.  TRL CONTACT WAS DISPATCHER DALE OTTO. J.T. BAKER CONTACT WAS CHARLIE RUFE.  AT 9:30PM, THE RINCCHEM RESPONSE TEAM MOBILIZED AND DEPARTED THE RINCHEM YARD 10:00 PM VIA THE RINCHEM EMERGENCY RESPONSE VEHICLE.  THE CREW WAS DIRECTED TO EXIT 96 OFF US INTERSTATE 40, THIRTY MILES EAST OF AMARILLO, TEXAS.  ARRIVAL TIME ON SITE AT LUV'S TRUCK STOP WAS 4:30 AM ON JANUARY 14, 1996.  TRL DRIVER RAY CHITSWARA WAS CONTACTED; DURING THE MEETING, LEAD TECHC ALFRED S. WAS INFORMED THAT AN ENTRY INTO THE TRAILER HAD BEEN DONE BY THE TRL DRIVER AND THAT THE LEAK APPEARED TO BE COMING FROM FOUR POLY 55 DRUMS ON A PALLET TWO THIRDS OF THE WAY INTO THE TRAILER.  ENTRY TEAM CONSISTING OF ALFRED S. AND JOHN F. USED LEVEL "B" PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT (PPE), WHICH INCLUDED KLEENGUARD TYVEK COVERALLS, RUBBER BOOTS, PVC GLOVES, AND SELF CONTAINED BREATHING APPARATUS (SCBA).  ENTRY WAS DIFFICULT, AS THE PALLETIZED PRODUCT WAS DOUBLE STACKED IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER; UPON REACHING THE POLY DRUMS, THE LEAK WAS CONFIRMED AS COMING FROM ONE DRUM CONTAINING POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE.  IT APPEARED THE TRL DRIVER HAD MADE AN ATTEMPT TO CONTAIN THE LEAK AS THERE WAS "KITTY LITTER"  ON AND AROUND THE LEAKING DRUM, AND THIS MATERIAL WAS REACTING WITH THE POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE. WHERE PUDDLED, THIS LIQUID WAS "BOILING" WHEN COMING INTO CONTACT WITH THE KITTY LITTER.  THE ENTRY TEAM APPLIED APPROXIMATELY 200LBS OF CALCINED CLAY ABSORBENT TO ALL THE FREE LIQUID IN THE TRAILER.  THE LEAK WAS CONTAINED TO THIS UNIT.  UNLOADING THE PRODUCT AT THE TRUCK STOP FOR FINAL CLEANUP WAS NOT FEASIBLE.  THE DECISION WAS MADE TO MOVE THE TRL TRUCK TRAILER TO THE RINCHEM YARD IN ALBUQUERQUE, NM WITH THE RINCHEM EMERGENCY RESPONSE VEHICLE ESCORTING.  THE TRUCKS DEPARTED AT 5:30 AM, ARRIVING AT THE RINCHEM FACILITY AT 11:30 AM ON JANUARY 14, 1996.  USING THE WAREHOUSE DOCK ALL OF THE MATERIAL FROM THE TRAILER WAS STAGED ONTO 10 MIL PLASTIC SHEETING AND THE LEAKINE CONTAINER WAS PLACED INTO AN 85 GALLON POLY OVERPACK DRUM.  MORE CLAY ABSORBENT WAS USED ON THE REMAINING FREE LIQUID IN THE TRAILER AND WAS SWEPT UP.  THE CHEMICAL REACTION WHERE THE LEAK OCCURRED HAD LEFT AN 18 INCH BY 36 INCH PORTION OF THE FLOOR EATEN AWAY, DOWN TO THE INSULATION PART OF THE TRAILER FLOOR.  LEAD TECH ALFRED S. RECOMMENDED THE TRAILER NOT BE USED TO TRANSPORT THE MATERIAL OVER THE ROAD UNTIL REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED TO THE FLOOR.  ALL OF THE PRODUCT FROM THE TRAILER WAS PROPERLY SEGREGATED AND STORED IN THE RICHEM WAREHOUSE UNTIL J.T. BAKER HAD ARRANGED FOR ANOTHER TRL TRUCK TO PICK UP THE LOAD AND COMPLETE THE TRANSPORTATION OF THE PRODUCT TO CALIFORNIA.  FINAL CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED ON THE DAMAGED TRAILER ON JANUAR

IN THE PROCESS OF DELIVERING SAD'S OF SULFURIC ACID TO EASTGATE PLUMBING, ONE FELL FROM THE PALLET THAT WAS BEING MOVED WITH AN ELECTRIC PALLETJACK. THE SAD FELL APPROXIMATELY 6" AND THE SIDE CRACKED, SPILLING APPROXIMATELY THREE GALLONS.  THE AREA WAS BLOCKED FROM PEDESTRIANS AND THE MATERIAL WAS QUICKLY CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP.  THE WEATHER WAS A MAJOR CONTRIBUTOR TO THIS.  THE FROZEN SNOW AND ICE CAUSED THE PALLETJACK TO BOUNCE. DELIVERIES WILL NO LONGER BE MADE TO THIS CUSTOMER DURING SNOW OR ICY WEATHER.

column168: CARGO TANK WAS BEING PUMPED OFF INTO A STORAGE TANK.  THE FITTING FROM THE HOSE TO THE PUMP CAME LOOSE, ALLOWING OIL TO BE PUMPED ONTO THE GROUND. KEITH WAS UNLOADING AT THE TEXACO LACT UNIT AT ISLE'S DOME.  THE LOCKING EARS ON THE CAM-LOCK FITTING ATTACHING THE HOSE TO THE TRUCKS PRODUCT PUMP VIBRATED LOOSE.  THE HOSE FELL LOOSE FROM THE PRODUCT PUMP ALLOWING OIL TO BE PUMPED ONTO THE GROUND.  THE OIL RAN OVER THE LOCATION AND INTO THE BARROW DITCH ALONG SIDE THE ROAD.  IN THE BARROW DITCH, THE OIL RAN THROUGH A CULVERT AND ONTO AMOCCO OWNED PROPERTY.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE: BASIN WESTERN, INC. WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL AT 10:30.  DWIGHT SPRINGER AND A HELPER WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE AT 11:00.  THE TRUCK DRIVER, KIETH STEVENSON, ALONG WITH BOB DANA AND GLENN LORANGER DID AS MUCH AS THEY COULD TO KEEP OIL FROM BEING TRACKED ONTO THE COUNTY ROAD.  DWIGHT ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT 15:00.  HE AND CLAYTON HARDY OF TEXACO SURVEYED THE SPILL AREA.  DWIGHT CALLED ME AT 15:30 TO REPORT THAT THE OIL HAD TRAVELED A SIGNIFICANT DISTANCE UNDER THE SNOW.  HE SAID A CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR WITH A BACK-HO WOULD BE NEEDED TO CLEAN UP THE MESS.  AFTER REPORTING THE EXTENT OF THE SPILL, DWIGHT BOUGHT A LOAD OF SAND AND PLACED A SAND DIKE AT THE FURTHEST EDGE OF THE OIL TO CONTAIN IT.  I CALLED JIM SHOWALTER OF S & K CONSTRUCTION AT 16:00.  HE WENT TO THE SCENE TO SURVEY THE SPILL AND TO DETERMINE THE BEST CLEAN-UP OPTIONS.  HE REPORTED THAT HE COULD DID SOME SOIL/WATER SEPARATION SIPHON/PITS TO COLLECT THE OIL AS THE WATER MOVED THROUGH THE AREA.  OVER TIME, THE SIPHON PITS WOULD COLLECT OIL WHERE IT COULD BE RECOVERED BY A VACCUM TRUCK. JIM AND CLAYTON HARDY DISCUSSED THE VIABILITY OF THAT FOR PERMISSION TO PROCEED.  I AGREED TO MEET JIM AT THE SCENE THE FOLLOWING MORNING AT 09:00.  THE FOLLOWING MORNING, 01/18/96, I, CLAYTON HARDY, MARK COOP, AND JIM SHOWALTER MET AT ISLES DOME.  CLAYTON HAD CONTACTED HIS SUPERVISORS AT TEXACO AND INFORMED US THAT THEY TOLD HIM THAT THEY DID NOT WANT TO WAIT FOR COLLECTION OF THE OIL OVER TIME.  THEY WANTED THE OIL CLEANED UP IMMEDIATELY.  WITH THAT IN MIND, WE DECIDED TO BUILD A LARGER DIKE AT THE LOWER EDGE OF THE OIL AND TO WASH THE OIL TO THE DIKE WITH HOT WATER AND A PRESSURE WASHER.  THE PRESSURE WASHER AND WATER WERE FURNISHED AND HAULED BY BETHELL TRUCKING CO.  WE BEGAN THE WASHING PROCESS AT 12:30 ON 01/18/96.  THE CLEAN-UP OPERATION WAS COMPLETE AT 18:00 ON 0/19/96.

WHILE TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON THE 210 FREEWAY ON THE TRANSITION ROAD TO THE 57 FREEWAY SOUTH IN THE GLENDORA AREA, THE DRIVER HEARD A LOUD BANG.  HE LOOKED IN THE MIRROR TO SEE THE REAR DOOR OF A ROLL OFF CONTAINER FLY OPEN.  HE IMMEDIATELY PULLED TO THE SIDE OF THE ROADWAY TO ASSESS WHAT HAD HAPPENED.  HE SAW THAT APPROXIMATELY 8 TO 10 BAGS OF THE ASBESTOS MATERIAL HAD DROPPED ONTO THE ROADWAY AND WAS NOT BEING HIT BY ON COMING TRAFFIC MAKING IT POSSIBLE TO RETRIEVE THEM.  HE CONTACTED THE OFFICES OF CONSOLIDATION WASTE INDUSTRIES BY RADIO AT APPROXIMATELY 9:40A.M. AND THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED.  THE CONSOLIDATED WASTE INDUSTRIES TEAM ARRIVED AT 10:10AM TO ASSESS THE EXTENT OF THE INCIDENT, THEN PLAN AND EXECUTE CLEANUP.  CAL TRANS AND THE CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL WERE ON SITE DURING ROADWAY CLOSURE AND CLEANUP.  L.A. COUNTY FIRE HAZMAT ASSUMMED ROLE OF LEAD AGENCY.  OES NUMBER 011653 WAS CONFIRMED.  CLEANUP INVOLVED THE PICKUP OF THE LARGER PIECES OF ASBESTOS CONTAINING MATERIALS (ACM) AND PLASTIC BAGS FOLLOWED BY THE MISTING AND SWEEPING OF SMALL PIECES.  THE REMAINING FINE GYPSUM WAS WET DOWN AND VACUUMED BY USE OF A HEPA VACCUM. ALL PERSONNEL WERE INQUIRED TO WEAR TYVEK COVERALLS, GLOVES, BOOTS AND FULL FACE AIR PURIFYING RESPIRATORS DURING THE COURSE OF ALL CLEANUP ACTIVITY.  ALL CONTAMINANTS RECOVERED WERE CONTAINED IN 55 GALLON STEEL DRUMS ON SITE.  THROUGHOUT THE CLEANUP PROCESS CONSOLIDATED WASTE INDUSTRIES AND THE AGENCIES ON SITE TALKED EXTENSIVELY TAKING CLEANUP CRITERIA AND DIRECTION FROM LOS ANGELES COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT.  THE SITE WAS DEEMED CLEAN AT 2:50PM ON JANUARY 8,1996 BY SAMIR IBRAHIM. column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON 1-16-96 AT APPROXIMATELY 3:40 PM KOCH TRUCK DRIVER, DARCY BRAATEN, LOADED WITH CRUDE OIL AND WAS DRIVING EAST ON RICHLAND COUNTY 201. THE EXACT LOCATION WAS 15 MILES OF THE INTERSECTION OF MONTANA 16 AND RICHLAND COUNTY 201. THE ROADS WERE CLEAR AND DRY. THE HIGHWAY IS A TWO LANE WITHOUT A SHOULDER. THE HIGHWAY IS NARROW WITH DROP OFFS ON BOTH SIDES. DARCY STATED HE LOOKED IN HIS DRIVER'S SIDE MIRROR AND WHEN HE LOOKED BACK TO THE HIGHWAY HIS TRUCK HAD DRIFTED TO THE RIGHT EDGE OF THE PAVEMENT. HE CORRECTED TO THE LEFT, FELT THE TRAILER WHEELS PULLING TO THE RIGHT AND KNEW THEY WERE OVER THE EDGE OF THE SHOULDER. THE TRAILER WENT DEEPER OVER THE EDGE UNTIL THE ENTIRE TRAILER WAS IN THE DITCH AND PULLING HIM SIDE WAYS. THE TRACTOR TURNED OVER ON THE RIGHT SIDE AND SLID TO A STOP. DARCY HAD HIS SEAT BELT ON AND CLIMBED OUT OF THE WRECKAGE. HE FELT NO INJURY IMMEDIATELY AND PUT OUT WARNING MARKERS. ALMOST IMMEDIATELY, A COUPLE STOPPED AT THE SCENE AND DARCY ASKED THEM TO PLEASE CALL THE SHERIFF AND KOCH CENTRAL COMMUNICATIONS. SHORTLY THEREAFTER, ANOTHER KOCH EMPLOYEE, DARYL VAIRA, ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AND HELPED SET UP SITE SECURITY. CENTRAL IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED OPA-90 QUALIFIED INDIVIDUAL, WES CHRISTENSEN, WHO IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED A KOCH RESPONSE TEAM TO THE SCENE. DARYL VAIRA AND DARCY BRAATEN MAINTAINED SITE SECURITY UNTIL THE AUTHORITIES ARRIVED. TRAFFIC WAS BLOCKED IN BOTH DIRECTIONS. THE KOCH RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED AND WITH THE COOPERATION OF THE LOCAL CONTRACTORS CLEARED THE ROAD AND CLEANED UP THE CRUDE OIL OFF THE ROAD. THE FOLLOWING DAY THE BALANCE OF THE CRUDE OIL WAS CLEANED FROM THE DITCHES. THE WASTE MATERIAL WAS TAKEN TO DISHON DISPOSAL, A CERTIFIED LAND FILL. CLEANUP EFFORTS OF ANY RESIDUE WILL CONTINUE UNTIL SITE TERMINATION IS APPROVED BY KELLY LOGAN, THE RICHLAND COUNTY SANITARIAN, AND THE MONTANA DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH. NO SURFACE WATER ARE IN DANGER OR WERE IN DANGER. THE AREA WILL BE CAREFULLY MONITORED BY KOCH UNTIL SITE TERMINATION IS APPROVED BY THE STATE OF MONTANA. THE CONTRACT FOR ANY ADDITIONAL INFORMATION IS FRANK RAFFAELL, REGULATIONS COORDINATOR OR WES CHRISTENSEN, DIVISION MANAGER AT 701-565-2296. THE ROOT CAUSE WAS DETERMINED TO BE HUMAN ERROR. THE CAUSE WAS THOUROUGHLY DISCUSSED WITH MULTIPLE SUPERVISOR AND THE DRIVER. THE LESSON LEARNED ARE BEING DISCUSSED WITH OTHER DRIVERS AT DRIVERS MEETING.

TANK CAR UTLX 71100 OBSERVED BY TRAIN PERSONNEL AT UNION PACIFIC ALEXANDRIA YARD TO BE SLOSHING LIQUID FROM THE TOP DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS. THE CAR WAS SET OUT AND ISOLATED WITHOUT INCIDENT. SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT B. G. BAREFIELD WAS NOTIFIED AND HE, IN TURN NOTIFIED THE LOUISANA STATE POLICE HAZ/MAT UNIT, THE LOUISANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, RAPIDES PARISH COMMUNICATION CENTER, CHEMTREC AND UPRR REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, T. M. ROBINSON. ROBINSON RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. ROBINSON DISCOVERED THAT THE LEAKAGE WAS THE RESULT OF A FAILED FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT. THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY APPEARED TO BE A MIDLAND MODEL "A-425" MOUNTED ON ITS OWN NOZZLE WITHIN THE REGULAR WORKING PLATFORM OF THE CAR. THE NOZZLE APPEARED TO HAVE AN INVERTED "T" PIPE BAFFLE. THE FAILED DISC WAS A CDC 100# AND WAS REPLACED WITH THE SAME TYPE BY ROBINSON. THE CAR WAS RELEASED ONTO DESTINATION. ROBINSON WAS ABLE TO TALK TO MR. ED PATTERSON WITH SUN COMPANY. PATTERSON WAS INFORMED OF THE INCIDENT AND THE CORRECTIVE ACTION TAKEN.

I RECEIVED A CALL FROM GLENDA DECKER (LEAD DISPATCHER) THAT OUR DRIVER, PAUL HEIN, HAD BEEN INVOLVED IN A ROLL-OVER ACCIDENT IN WISCONSIN.  GLENDA RELAYED A MOBILE TELEPHONE NUMBER TO CONTACT MR. TONY OLDIGS, A MEMBER OF THE LYNDON STATION FIRE DEPARTMENT, WHO WAS ON SIGHT.  10:15 P.M.  I SPOKE WITH MR. OLDIGS REGARDING THE CONDITION OF OUR DRIVER, MR. HEIN, THE CONDITION OF THE VEHICLE, AND ANY SPILL THAT MIGHT HAVE OCCURRED.  I WAS INFORMED THAT MR. HEIN WAS IN "GOOD SHAPE" BUT HAD BEEN TRANSPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL BY AMBULANCE AS A PRECAUTION.  NO OTHER VEHICLES HAD BEEN INVOLVED IN THE ACCIDENT.  THE TRACTOR/TRAILER WAS ON IT'S SIDE BUT NO LEAKING COMPARTMENTS HAD BEEN DETECTED.  THE FRONT AND REAR COMPARTMENTS CONTAINED PRODUCT BUT THE MIDDLE COMPARTMENT WAS EMPTY.  I WAS INFORMED THAT, BECAUSE THE TRAILER WAS PARTIALLY LOADED, IT WOULD HAVE TO BE DRAINED BEFORE BEING UP-RIGHTED.  OPTIONS WERE DISCUSSED AND IT WAS DECIDED THAT THE PRODUCT REMOVAL AND UP-RIGHTING OF THE TRAILER WOULD WAIT UNTIL DAYLIGHT.  MR. ODLIGS STATIONED A VEHICLE WITH EMERGENCY LIGHTS AND A FIREMAN AT THE SCENE TO SECURE THE AREA.  I MADE ARRANGEMENTS FOR A TANKER TO BE ON SITE AT DAYLIGHT FOR THE PRODUCT REMOVAL.  11:00 P.M.  I SPOKE WITH PAUL HEIN AT THE REEDSBURG MEDICAL CENTER IN REEDSBURG, WISCONSIN, AS HE WAS BEING RELEASED.  HE STATED THAT HE WAS OK WITH THE EXCEPTION OF A LITTLE SORENESS IN HIS LEFT SHOULDER BUT WAS UPSET WITH HIMSELF THAT THE INCIDENT HAD OCCURRED.  HE INFORMED ME THAT HE HAD NOT BEEN ISSUED A TICKET.  I EXPLAINED MY PLANS TO UNLOAD AND UP-RIGHT THE TRACTOR/TRAILER.  WE DISCUSSED PAUL'S PLANS FOR THAT EVENING.  HE DECIDED TO HAVE THE JUNEAU COUNTY POLICE DROP HIM AT A LOCAL HOTEL WHERE HE WOULD GET SOME REST AND CHECK IN WITH ME THE NEXT DAY.  I MET WITH UNIBULK DRIVER, LENARD ROCKNOWSKI WHO HAD A CLEAN SINGLE COMPARTMENT TRAILER AND THE EQUIPMENT NEED TO DRAIN THE DAMAGED TRAILER.  WE AGREED TO MEET AT LYNDON STATION, WISCONSIN, AND ASSESS THE SITUATION.  I THEN PICKED UP THE COMPANY VAN AND SOME PAPERWORK AND PROCEEDED TO LYNDON STATION.  6:00 A.M. JANUARY 9, 1996  MR. ROCKNOWSKI, OF UNIBULK TANK LINES, MR. OLDIGS, OF THE LYNDON STATION FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND I MET FOR APPROXIMATELY 45 MINUTES TO DISCUSS THE EVENTS OF THE PREVIOUS EVENING.  WE DECIDED TO WAIT UNTIL DAYLIGHT BEFORE LEAVING FOR THE ACCIDENT SCENE.  7:00 A.M.  AT THE SCENE WE MET WITH DON CAUGHLIN, THE FIRE CHIEF, BRIEFLY DISCUSSED THE VENT LEADING UP TO THAT POINT AND DECIDED TO BEGIN THE DRAINING OPERATION. BOTH ENDS OF COUNTY HIGHWAY HH WERE SECURED BY TWO MEMBERS OF THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND JUNEAU COUNTY POLICEMAN.  HIGHWAY HH IS NOT A HEAVY USED HIGHWAY SO DISRUPUTION TO LOCAL TRAFFIC WAS MINIMAL.  MR. ROCKNOWSKI POISITIONED HIS TRACTOR/TRAILER ALONG SIDE THE OVERTURNED VEHICLE AND THE OFF-LOADING OPERATION BEGAN.  8:00 A.M.  I CALLED THE LOCAL HOTEL TO CHECK ON THE CONDITION OF OUR DRIVER AND WAS INFORMED THAT HE WAS DOING WELL. PAUL INFORMED ME THAT THE REAR COMPARTMENT CONT

column168: ATCHESON'S EXPRESS DRIVER, JEFF CURTIS, WAS LOADED AT PDL WITH FOUR TOTE BINS IN WHICH TWO WERE PALLETIZED AND TWO WERE NOT.  THE TOTE BINS ARE APPROXIMATELY 48"X48"X48".  TOHE TOTE BINS CONTAINED A MIXTURE OF DIPHENYL ETHANE AND 4,4' DIISOCYANATE.  THESE WERE LOADED TOWARD THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  THERE WERE 8 OTHER DRUMS LOADED ON THE LEFT FRONT OF THE TRAILER, AND 3 CARTONS OF RUBBER PRODUCTS LOADED ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRAILER.  OUR DRIVER DEPARTED PDL, IN ORANE, TO DELIVER SOME PRODUCT TO CYRUS BUSINESS FURNITURE IN COMPTON.  HE EXITED THE WESTBOUND 91 AT WILMINGTON AND PROCEEDED SOUTH ON WILMINGTON TO CASHDAN.  HE THEN TURNED LEFT TO ARRIVE AT CYRUS BUSINESS FURNITURE.  UPON ARRIVAL AT CYRUS, WHILE BACKING UP THE TRUCK INTO THEIR DRIVERWAY, HE NOTICED SOME LIQUID LEAKING FROM WHAT HE THOUGHT WAS THE TRACTOR.  HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF THE TRACTOR.  HE GOT OUT TO INVESTIGATE AND FOUND LIQUID COMING FROM THE TRIALER.  HE WENT DIRECTLY TO A PHONE AND INFORMED THE ATCHESON'S EXPRESS' DISPATCHER THAT ONE OF THE PALLETIZED TOTE BINS, LOCAED ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE TRAILER TOWARD THE REAR, WAS LEAKING.  DISPTACH IMMEDIATELY CALED PDL TO ALERT THEM OF THE INCIDENT.  PDL CONTACTED A PRIVATE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CLEAN UP COMPANY.  PACIFIC RESOURCE RECOVERY (LOCATED IN LOS ANGELES, 800 499-7145).  BY THE TIME OUR DRIVER FOT OFF THE PHONE, THE POLICE WERE PULLING UP THE SCENE OF THE INCIDENT.  I LEFT MY OFFICE IN ORANGE AND WENT TO CYRUS SO THAT I COULD ASSESS THE SITUATION.  UPON ARRIVAL, I QUESTIONED THE DRIVER WHAT HAD HAPPENED.  HE REPORTED THAT NOTHING UNUSUAL HAPPENED DURING THE ROUTE SUCH AS BRAKING HARD, OR TURNING FAST.  HE DID MENTION THAT ON WILMINGTON, WHILE HE WAS DRIVING IN THE LEFT LANE GOING SOUTH, THERE WERE SOME UNMARKED RAILROAD TRACKS THAT GAVE HIM A SUBSTANTIAL JOLT AS HE RODE OVER THEM, EVEN THOUGH HE WAS GOING WELL UNDER THE SPEED LIMIT.  AT THIS POINT THOUGH, HE STILL DIDN'T THINK ANYTHING HAD HAPPENED TO THE CONTENTS IN THE TRAILER.  AFTER THE FACT, IT WAS NOTED THAT APPROXIMATLEY 80-100 FEET, SOUTH OF THE RAILROAD TRACKS, THE ROAD HAS AN INCLINE.  IT IS AT THIS POINT THAT THE MATERIAL IS FIRST NOTICED ON THE PAVEMENT.  CURRENTLY, THE PROBABLE CAUSE OF THE SPILL IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION, THEREFORE, NO RECOMMENDATION CAN BE GIVEN TO PREVENT A FUTURE SPILL.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY JOE GUERRERO, ASSISTANT GENERAL MANAGER, HARBOR BELT LINE RAILROAD (JOINTLY OWNED BY UP-SP-ATSF), WHO ADVISED THERE WAS A TANKCAR OF LIQUIFIED PETROLEUM GAS LEAKING AT THE HBL YARD LOCATED IN WILMINGTON. ASSISTANT GUERRERO WAS REQUESTING ASSISTANCE IN DEALING WITH THE LEAKING CONTENTS.  MEMBERS OF THE UNOCAL FIRE DEPAREMTN HAD INSPECTED THE CAR AND WAS MONITORING CONCENTRATIONS OF FLAMMABLE VAPORS.  THEY WERE LOOKING FOR HELP FROM THE RAILROAD, ALONG WITH LOS ANGELES CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT, WHO WAS ALSO ON SITE.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE HBL YARD AND MET WITH UNOCAL PERSONNEL, LA CITY FIRE (STATION 49), AND MR. GUERRERO.  THE UNOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL HAD MONITORED CONCENTRATIONS OF VAPORS EXCEEDING 5% OF THE LEL NEAR THE TOP PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  THEY DID NOT OPEN THE COVER PLATE TO INSPECT THE VALVES, AS THEY WERE NOT FAMILIAR WITH THE VALVING ARRANGEMENT OF THE CAR.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH THE FIRE DEPARTMENT TO PROVIDE EXPOSURE COVERAGE WHILE A MEMBER FROM UNOCAL ESCORTED MANAGER COOPER TO INSPECT THE CAR.  AFTER SUITING UP AND ENTERING THE VICINITY OF THE CAR, MONITORING ESTABLISHED THE GROUND LEVEL VAPORS AT 2% OF THE LEL.  UPON OPENING THE COVER PLATE, FOUND THE "B" END LIQUID VALVE TO BE COMPLETELY FROZEN OVER.  THE VALVE HANDLE WAS IN THE CLOSED POSITION, WITH NO ADDITIONAL MOVEMENT ALLOWED.  THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS OPERATING WITH PRODUCT BOILING AROUND THE SEAT INSIDE OF THE RETAINER BODY OF THE VALVE.  A PRESSURE CHECK FROM THE SAMPLE LINE INDICATED AT 260 POUNDS.  ATTEMPTS TO GUAGE THE CAR AT THE SLIP TUBE GUAGE DEVICE MET WITH NEGATIVE RESULTS AS THE GUAGE ROD WAS FROZEN IN PLACED AND WOULD NOT MOVE, EVEN AFTER LOOSENING THE PACKING GLAND.  ALTHOUGH THE CAR COULD NOT BE GUAGED, IT WOULD BE APPARENT THAT IT WAS OVERLOADED DUE TO THE PRODUCT ESCAPING.  FROM THE SAFETY VENT.  THE SAFETY VENT RETAINER STEM WAS TAPPED SEVERAL TIMES, WHICH REDUCED THE LIQUID FLOW ROUGHLY 75%, INDICATING THERE MAY HAVE BEEN SOME ICE OR DEBRIS AT THE O RINGS BELOW THE RETAINER.  THE ICE AT THE LIQUID VALVE WAS CHIPPED AWAY AND ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE NUTS TO THE COMPRESSION RING TO THE VALVE STEM, HOWEVER, WAS UNABLE TO GET ANY MOVEMENT.  THE NUTS MAY HAVE BEEN FULLY SEATED, OR THE ICES VALVE ASSEMBLY MAY HAVE PREVENTED ANY ADDITIONAL MOVEMENT.  AS THERE WAS NO VISIBLE LIQUID FLOWING FROM THE VALVE, IT WAS DECIDED TO MOVE THE CAR INTO THE UNOCAL FACILITY WHERE IT COULD BE OFF LOADED.  ONCE THE CAR IS MADE EMPTY, IT WILL BE MOVED BACK TO COLORADO REFINING, WHERE IT WILL BE SHOPPED FOR REPAIRS.

ON THURSDAY 1/18/96, FRA INSPECTOR JAMES DUNCAN CONDUCTED REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS ON A GROUP OF TANK CARS AT PORT ALLEN, LOUISIANA. NATX 25497 WAS INSPECTED AT THAT TIME AND FOUND TO HAVE THE AIR INLET PLUG LOOSE, ONE OF EIGHT MANWAY SWING BOLTS LOOSE AND THERE WAS NO GASKET BEWEEN THE MANWAY LID AND NOZZLE. THE MISSING GASKET RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT WHEN THE CAR WAS MOVED.  THE SPILLAGE APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN CONFINED TO THE TOP AND SIDES OF THE CAR.  DUNCAN NOTIFICATION UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD, MANAGER OF MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE JIM OSBURN AND REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY T. M. ROBINSON.  OSBURN ROBINSON INSTALLED A TEMPORARY GASKET OF GORTEX AND SECURED THE CAR FOR MOVEMENT.  BASED ON THE RECOMENDATION OF DUNCAN,ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH UPRR MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS JOE CALLAWAY TO PLACETHIS CAR AND SEVEN OTHER CARS BACK TO THE SHIPPERS FACILITY FOR FORRECTIVE.  ACTION. DUNCAN TO CONTACT RESPONSIBLE PARTIES AT THE SHIPPERS FACILITY ON FRIDAY 1/19/96. ROBINSON SPOKE WITH MS. WANDA VANNORDEN, MANAGER AT CHEM RAIL'S PORT ALLEN FACILITY ON 1/19/96 AND INFORMED HER OF THE INCIDENT.  SHE STATED THAT PERSONNEL AT HER FACILITY WOULD INSPECT THE CARS.

column168: ON 012696 AT APPROXIMATELY 630AM MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, GEOGGREY REEDER, RECEIVED A CALL FROM MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS, CARL BROUGHTON, WHO REPORTED THE ABOVE CAR LEAKING FROM THE TOP.  THE SWITCH CREW REPORTED THAT WHEN THE CAR WAS SWITCHED INTO THE BOWL TRACK AND IT COUPLED, IT SPLASHED PRODUCT.  COUPLED INTO THE STANDING CARS.  REEDER INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND NO EVIDENCE OF PRODUCT SPLASHING ON THE TOP OF THE CAR.  NO OBVIOUS DEFECTS WERE NOTED.  THE BOLTS SECURING THE BLIND BE THE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE.  THERE WAS PRODUCT STANDING IN THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE HOUSING.  IT APPEARS THE VALVE OPENED UPON IMPACT DUE TO HYDRAULIC SURGING.  THE VALVE IS LOCATED ON THE MANWAY COVER PLATE, IN THE CENTER OF THE CAR.  SINCE THERE WERE NO OBVIOUS SOURCES OF RELEASE, REEDER HAD A SWITCH CREW AGAIN "KICK" THE CAR INTO THE STANDING CARS WHILE HE LOOKED FOR SIGNS OF A RELEASE.  UPON IMPACT, NO RELEASE WAS NOTED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR NORMAL MOVEMENT.  THE SHIPPER AND CHEMTREC WERE NOTIFIED.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS DISPATCHED TO THE LOCATION TO PUMP OUT AND RECOVER THE PRODUCT FOR DELIVERY TO ANOTHER LOCATION. OUR DRIVER TOOK A MEASUREMENT OF THE PRODUCT IN THE UST AND DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS 1.950 GALLONS IN THE UST. HE THEN ATTEMPTED TO PUT THE PRODUCT IN THE 2,000 GALLON COMPARTMENT OF THE TRAILER. AS THE UST EMPTIED, THE PUMP ON THE TRACTOR BEGAN TO SUCK AIR, WHICH CAUSED THE PRODUCT, NOW IN THE TRAILER TO BUBBLE. THIS BUBBLING ACTION FORCED BETWEEN 7 AND 10 GALLONS OF PRODUCT OUT OF THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE PARKING AREA OF THE STORE. NEW YORK DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS CONTACTED AND ASSIGNED SPILL #95-13682 TO THIS INCIDENT.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS SOUTH BOUND ON KY 101.  HE STATED HE HIT A SLICK SPOT AND LOST CONTROL OF THE RIG.  THE TRAILER WENT INTO A DITCH.  HE WAS ABLE TO GET THE TRACTOR BACK ON THE ROAD BUT OVERTURNED IN THE MIDDLE OF THE ROAD. HE WAS LOADED WITH CRUDE OIL AND IT IS ESTIMATED APPROXIMATLEY 26 TO 50 GALLONS OF CRUDE OIL WERE RELEASED.  THE LEAKING COMPARTMENT WAS PLUGGED AND THEY DUG SEVERAL SHALLOW HOLES TO COLLECT THE RELEASED CRUDE.  AT THE DIRECTION OF DWIGHT CARDWELL, THE EMERGENCY RESPONDER ON SITE FROM BOWLING GREEN REGIONAL OFFICE OF THE DIVISION OF WATER, THE SOMERSET ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES IGNITED THE CRUDE TO PREVENT FURTHER MIGRATION OF THE CRUDE.  THE NEXT DAY, THE IMPACTED AREA LOCATED ON THE JOE LOWE FARM WAS EXCAVATED AND STOCKPILED IN PREPARATION OF DISPOSAL.  SAMPLES WERE TAKEN OF THE EXCAVATED AREA TO CONFIRM REMOVAL OF THE RELEASED CRUDE OIL.  ADDITIONAL CLEANUP IS AWAITING APPROVAL OF AN ENCROACHMENT PERMIT BY THE DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION.

column168: SORT LEAD VANESSA PAULEY REPORTED A SHIPMENT EMITING AN ODOR IN BUILDING K OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON OHIO 45177.  P/T HAZMAT SPILL TECHNICIAN THEO GHOSTONE RESPONDED TO THE ODOR.  UPON ARRIVAL HE FOUND A RED PLASTIC BAG SHOWING SIGNS OF LEAKAGE WITH AN ODOR OF FUEL.  INSIDE THE PLASTIC BAG HE FOUND A BROWN FIBREBOARD BOX CONTAINING 8 PLASTIC JARS WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES.  PACKED IN VERMICULITE ABSORBENT.  THREE OF THE PLASTIC JARS SHOWED SIGNS OF LEAKAGE DUE TO UNSECURE CLOSURES.  EACH JAR CONTAINS APPROXIMATELY 6 OUNCES OF LIQUID.  IDENTIFICATION OF THE LIQUID WAS UNKNOWN AT THE TIME OF THE SPILL.  A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED FROM THE SHIPPER.  THEO PH" D THE LIQUID, NEUTRAL READING.  HE PLACED THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT INSIDE 2 PLASTIC BAGS, TAGGED IT TO BE HELD AND THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INSIDE THE FLAMMABLE CABINET AT THE HAZ MAT SORT.  MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER, CONTENTS OF THE JARS HAS BEEN IDENTIFIED AS: FLAMMABLE LIQUID N.O.S., (TRIMETHYL BENZENE, DIMETHYL BENZENE), 3, UN1993, PG 111.  SHIPMENT REMAINS UNDER LOCK AND KEY IN THE HAZ MAT SORT AREA PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THERE IS NO MARKING, LABELS, OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS ARE A REGULATED MATERIAL.  THE INTERNATIONAL EXPRESS ENVELOPE CONTAINS A COVER LETTER REGARDING THE SHIPMENT AND A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET.  BOTH OF THESE DOCUMENTS WERE DAMAGED BY THE SPILL AND HAVE BEEN RENDERED VIRTUALLY ILLEGIBLE.  THERE WERE 2 EMPLOYEE'S IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR FROM THIS SHIPMENT.

column168: DRIVER STRUCK TANKS BEFORE DELIVERY, BUT DID NOT REFER TO TANK CALIBRATION CHART BEFORE STARTING TO DELIVER PRODUCT.  WHEN TANK CHART WAS FINALLY CHECKED IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE COMPARTMENTS OF THE TRAILER BEING UNLOADED WOULD NOT FIT IN THE STORAGE TANKS.  THE DRIVER ALSO FAILED TO STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT WHEN HE WAS MAKING A PHONE CALL REGARDING THE PROBLEM.  WHEN THE DRIVER RETURNED TO THE TRUCK, GASOLINE WAS COMING OUT OF A LOOSE VAPOR RECOVERY HOSE AT THE TRAILER VAPOR RETURN LINE.  WHEN THE TANK FILLED PRODUCT ENTERED THE VAPOR RECOVERY HOSE THROUGH THE COAXIAL ELBOW.  THE DRIVER STOPPED THE FLOW, CALLED FIRE DEPT.  AND COMPANY OFFICE. column168: THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE STATED THAT HE WAS PROCEEDING ON HWY 32, ISLE OF WIGHT, VIRGINIA TO DELIVER GASOLINE TO RED APPLE MARKET 59, HWY 32, EDENTON, NC.
